{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17516938","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17516938"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:48:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:48:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12730"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12730","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12730"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.53,0.07,0.13,0.16]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5185"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57011"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5185","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5185"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question","status":"accepted","createdAt":"2023-04-12T04:04:04+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-09T20:52:00+09:30","updatedAction":"updated","acceptedAt":"2023-12-07T08:29:41+10:30","editorNotifiedAt":null,"feedbackAt":"2025-09-03 23:18:42"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12730"}},"updatedBy":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"2888"}},"author":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"7098"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42460"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"687"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1098"},{"type":"tags","id":"2341"},{"type":"tags","id":"2356"},{"type":"tags","id":"2705"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8784"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8800"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10366"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13815"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17674"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46700"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46701"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46702"}]},"lastContribution":{"data":null},"lastRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42460"}},"lastActivity":{"data":null},"lastFeedback":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57011","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/57011"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old female is brought to the Emergency Department at night in a confused state by her roommate after she was found to be vomiting excessively and behaving abnormally. Collateral history from the roommate reveals that the patient was found with multiple empty medication bottles, after a visit to the pharmacy in the morning. Past medical history is significant only for chronic back pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, the patient is disoriented, not following commands appropriately and not responding appropriately to questions. Vital signs are as follows: temperature 38.5 \u00b0C, pulse 110 beats/min and respiratory rate 30 breaths/min. Blood pressure is within normal range. Lung and abdominal examination are unremarkable. The patient has a Glasgow Coma Scale (GCS) score of 10, with the following breakdown: eye-opening response 3, verbal response 2, motor response 5.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn ECG showed sinus tachycardia with a normal QT interval.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBlood investigations are as follows:\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate intervention?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hemodialysis","Intravenous sodium bicarbonate","Intravenous midazolam","Urgent endotracheal intubation","Oral Activated charcoal"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation, along with the concerning collateral history, are concerning for \u003Cstrong\u003Edrug toxicity\u003C/strong\u003E. A \u003Cstrong\u003Emetabolic acidosis\u003C/strong\u003E is evident from the low arterial pH and low bicarbonate. The expected response to metabolic acidosis would be hyperventilation to lower PaCO2, the degree of which can be calculated using Winter\u0027s formula (part of the Boston Method): Expected PaCO2 = (1.5 x serum HCO3)+(8\u00b12). Entering the values from the blood gas gives us an expected PaCO2 value of 30.5\u00b12mmHg, which is greater than the actual value which is 25mmHg, indicating a concomitant primary \u003Cstrong\u003Erespiratory alkalosis\u003C/strong\u003E. This combination is a classical finding in \u003Cstrong\u003Esalicylate toxicity\u003C/strong\u003E, a class of drugs (including aspirin) the patient likely had access to with the history of chronic back pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESalicylate poisoning can lead to a variety of metabolic disorders. Direct stimulation of the cerebral medulla causes\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003Ehyperventilation and subsequently respiratory alkalosis. As the salicylate is metabolized, it causes an uncoupling of oxidative phosphorylation in the mitochondria leading to increased anaerobic metabolism and increased lactate formation. This lactic acid, with a slight contribution from salicylate metabolites,\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003Eresults in a metabolic acidosis\u003Cstrong\u003E.\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESodium bicarbonate\u003C/strong\u003E is given intravenously and works by enhancing the elimination of salicylates via \u003Cstrong\u003Eurinary alkalisation. \u003C/strong\u003ESalicylates are weak acids, and so in the presence of alkaline urine exist in their ionised state, unable to cross the tubular cell membrane and return to the blood stream. This is known as \u003Cstrong\u003Eion trapping\u003C/strong\u003E, resulting in increased urinary excretion. Sodium bicarbonate is the mainstay of treatment for salicylate toxicity. A urinary catheter is also usually inserted, to monitor urine pH.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHemodialysis\u003C/strong\u003E (or \u003Cstrong\u003Erenal replacement therapy) \u003C/strong\u003Eis effective for the treatment of salicylate toxicity but \u003Cstrong\u003Erarely required\u003C/strong\u003E. It is indicated when urinary alkalisation is not possible, very high or rising serum salicylate levels despite gastric decontamination and bicarbonate therapy, or severe acidaemia or renal failure (none of which are present in this patient).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIV midazolam\u003C/strong\u003E is a benzodiazepine commonly used for the treatment of \u003Cstrong\u003Eseizures\u003C/strong\u003E, which may be present in salicylate poisoning, thought to be due to CNS hypoglycaemia. Since this patient has no seizure activity, this answer is incorrect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrgent endotracheal intubation\u003C/strong\u003E involves the placement of a breathing tube into the patient\u0027s airway, usually in response to r\u003Cstrong\u003Eespiratory failure or a threatened airway\u003C/strong\u003E. Though this patient\u0027s GCS score of 10 alone does not warrant urgent intubation, If her GCS deteriorates to the point that she is unable to protect her airway, intubation may become necessary. Intubation in these patients is challenging, as the removal of the respiratory compensation could result in a worsening acidaemia, cardiac arrest and death. Concomitant intravenous sodium bicarbonate boluses and urgent haemodialysis is often required if intubation is necessary.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral activated charcoal\u003C/strong\u003E is used for \u003Cstrong\u003Edecontamination \u003C/strong\u003Eup to 8 hours following ingestion in a calm, cooperative patient. In this case, the patient\u0027s altered mental status and vomiting significantly increase the risk of aspiration, and so should not be given unless via a nasogastric tube if the patient were intubated for another reason. Additionally, it is unclear if the patient has presented in the appropriate timeframe for decontamination.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere is \u003Cstrong\u003Eno \u003C/strong\u003Especific antidote for salicylate toxicity, and the mainstay of treatment is urinary alkalisation and supportive therapies. Co-ingestion must also be considered in all cases, with alcohol, paracetamol and tricyclic antidepressants being common culprits.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The clinical presentation of salicylate toxicity can be non-specific and can include confusion, altered mental status, nausea and vomiting, tinnitus, and hyperventilation.","Urinary alkalisation with intravenous sodium bicarbonate is the mainstay of management in salicylate poisoning, along with other supportive therapies."],"references":["Runde TJ, Nappe TM. Salicylates Toxicity. [Updated 2022 Jul 11]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2023 Jan-."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42460"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12730"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20260"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20260","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20260"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/a76kvVOeAvtw9BhyFDIk1efelFayP6.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/a76kvVOeAvtw9BhyFDIk1efelFayP6.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":993,"height":756}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42460","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/42460"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-23T19:33:56+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-23T19:34:41+10:30","number":11,"notes":"Added an example of a salicylate drug.","plagiarismCheckedAt":"2024-10-23T19: